
%#############################################################
\chapter{Resource intensity of economic activity~\Rparen{}}
\label{chap:resource_intensity}
%#############################################################
%\epigraph{The conservation of natural resources is the fundamental problem.
% Unless we solve that problem it will avail us little to solve all the others.}
%{Theodore Roosevelt}
\epigraph{Without natural resources, life itself is impossible. From birth to 
death, natural resources, transformed for human use, feed, clothe, shelter, and
transport us. \ldots
% Upon them we depend for every material necessity, comfort, convenience, and protection in our lives.
Without abundant resources\index{resources, abundant}, prosperity is out of reach.}
{Gifford Pinchot\index{Pinchot, Gifford}}

The previous chapter addressed the sustainability implications of 
economic affluence, the \mft{A} term in the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity} (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}, 
repeated below for convenience). 
Because the economy is society's metabolism\index{economic metabolism},
economic growth and increasing affluence
mean increasing use of natural resources and emission of wastes\index{waste}. 
This chapter explores the sustainability implications of acquisition and consumption of resources, 
which, when divided by GDP, becomes the resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}.

\begin{equation} 
  \iparx            \tag{\ref{eq:IPARX}}
\end{equation}

Whether we are aware of it or not, 
all plant, animal, and human life on Earth depends on natural resources, 
provisioned by the ecosystem\index{ecosystem}; 
see Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}.
Where would you be without air and water to breathe and drink?
Without minerals\index{minerals} to make cars?
Without timber\index{timber} to build homes?
Without healthy soil to grow food?
Without oceans\index{ocean} and an atmosphere\index{atmosphere} to accept wastes\index{waste}?
Without coal\index{coal}, oil\index{crude oil}, and methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)}
to make electricity\index{electricity}, gasoline\index{gasoline}, and natural gas\index{natural gas}?
Nowhere.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Definitions}
\label{sec:resource_intensity_definitions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

When discussing resource use, knowledge of several key terms is helpful.


%..............................
\paragraph{Resources}
%..............................

We use the term ``resource'' to mean a primary input to the economy. 
As such, a resource is something obtained from the natural world.
It is something provisioned by the ecosystem\index{ecosystem}, to use the language 
of Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}.
Timber\index{timber} is a resource. Iron ore\index{iron ore} is a resource. Water is a resource.
Each resource can be transformed many times within the economy.
Timber\index{timber} might become 2$\times$4s, plywood\index{plywood}, toothpicks\index{toothpick}, or mulch\index{mulch}.
Iron ore\index{iron ore} might become steel\index{steel}, then sheet metal\index{sheet metal}, and
then a toaster\index{toaster}.
Water might become ice, a sports drink, or Play-Doh\index{Play-Doh}.
The process of pulling a resource into the economy is called \textbf{extraction}\index{extraction}.
Equation~\ref{eq:PCbalance} indicates that everything that is extracted is used
for productive purposes.


%..............................
\paragraph{Efficiency and efficacy}
%..............................

An efficiency is a ratio of output to input, 
where both output and input have the same units.
A furnace that burns a quantity of natural gas\index{natural gas} that releases 100 BTUs of heat might
only deliver 96 of those BTUs to your house.
Such a furnace has an efficiency of 96\% (BTUs delivered per BTUs input).
(See Section~\ref{sec:heating_and_cooling}
for more on furnace efficiency and a related metric,
Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)}.)
A natural-gas power plant\index{natural-gas power plant} might burn gas at a rate that releases 300 MW of heat to generate
100 MW of electricity\index{electricity}. 
Such a power plant has an efficiency of 33.3\%.
In both cases, the input and output have the same units of energy, BTUs for the furnace
and MW for the power plant.

In contrast, 
an efficacy\index{efficacy} is like an efficiency, except the output (in the numerator)
and the input (in the denominator) have 
different units.
A vehicle's \textbf{fuel economy}\index{fuel economy}, measured in miles per gallon, is an efficacy\index{efficacy}, 
because the units in numerator (miles) are different from units in the denominator (gallons).
Tonnes of freight moved per liter of fuel consumed is another efficacy. 


%..............................
\paragraph{Resource intensity of economic activity}
%..............................

An intensity\index{intensity} is a ratio of inputs to outputs, 
usually with different units in numerator and denominator. 
The \mft{R} term in Equation \ref{eq:IPARX} is the resource intensity of economic activity.
\mft{R} is defined as
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:R}
  \mft{R} \equiv \frac{\text{resource extraction rate}}{\text{GDP}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
\mft{R} measures the total resources (the input) used by the economy to create a
total amount of economic output (measured by GDP).
Because \mft{R} is the ratio of input/output, 
\mft{R} is an intensity.

Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} shows consumption rates of some natural resources,
aggregated into important categories of 
construction minerals\index{construction minerals}, 
ores and industrial minerals\index{industrial minerals},
fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}, and 
biomass\index{biomass}.
In 2005, the world economy used about
19~Gt of biomass\index{biomass}, 
23~Gt of construction minerals\index{construction minerals}, 
11.6~Gt of fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}, and
5.7~Gt of ores\index{ores} and industrial minerals\index{industrial minerals}
to produce about \$81.5 trillion dollars of GDP. 
One Gt is 10$^\text{9}$~tonnes (or 10$^{\text{12}}$~kg) and a trillion dollars is \$10$^{\text{12}}$.
Thus, each dollar of GDP used about 
0.23~kg of biomass\index{biomass}, 
0.28~kg of construction minerals\index{construction minerals},
0.14~kg of fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}, and
0.07~kg of ores\index{ores} and industrial minerals\index{industrial minerals}.
A full accounting of the resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}
yields a long list of numbers, like a huge grocery list,
each number giving the amount of a single resource needed to make \$1 of GDP. 
This chapter discusses sustainability implications for a few resources,
with energy providing the prime example of resource intensity of the economy. 


