Resource intensity can be measured and quantified at the world level,
as in the examples above.
Alternatively, resource intensity can be quantified per country or per economic sector.
Clearly, the manufacturing sector of the economy requires resources to function.
Raw materials (such as copper\index{copper (Cu)} and minerals\index{minerals}) are required to make
finished goods (such as sewing machines\index{sewing machine} and mobile phones\index{mobile phone}).
But all sectors, even the service sector, need resources.
Consider the simple example of a haircut\index{haircut}.
The stylist commutes to the salon in a vehicle
(which requires iron ore\index{iron ore}, copper\index{copper (Cu)}, and other natural resources to manufacture; 
perhaps refined liquid fuel to operate; and 
an atmosphere\index{atmosphere} that is a source of oxygen and which absorbs CO$_2$ and water, the products of combustion).
The stylist uses electric clippers and a hairdryer\index{hairdryer} during each appointment
(which require both natural resources to manufacture and electricity\index{electricity} to operate).
You sit in a fancy chair 
(which contains metals and plastics) and
drive to and from the appointment
(on roads made of tar or cement).
There is no escaping the dependence on resources to run an economy, 
even in the service sector. 


%..............................
\paragraph{Primary vs.\ final vs.\ useful energy}\index{primary energy}\index{final energy}\index{useful energy}
%..............................

Imagine a coal-fired power plant\index{coal-fired power plant}
that generates electricity\index{electricity} to charge
an electric car\index{electric vehicle (EV)}. 
Coal\index{coal} is a \textbf{primary energy}\index{primary energy} source. 
The electricity\index{electricity} sold to consumers is considered to be a \textbf{final energy}\index{final energy} carrier.%
\footnote{
  Note that the term ``final'' comes from economics,
  where electricity\index{electricity} purchases by consumers are 
  counted in ``final demand.''
}
%
Hydro\index{hydro electricity}, solar\index{solar electricity}, and
wind\index{wind electricity} are primary energy\index{primary energy} sources. 
So are crude oil\index{crude oil} and methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)}.
In contrast, gasoline\index{gasoline} is a refined fuel. 
As such, gasoline\index{gasoline} is the product of 
a refinery that converts crude oil\index{crude oil} to refined fuels. 
Likewise, natural uranium\index{uranium (U)} is a primary energy\index{primary energy} carrier that must be converted into 
fissionable uranium\index{uranium (U)} fuel before it can be used
in a nuclear power plant\index{nuclear power plant} to generate electricity\index{nuclear electricity}.
The oil refinery or nuclear-fuel enrichment process can be evaluated for their
energy return on investment (EROI)\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}; 
see Section~\ref{sec:masterE}.
EROI is a type of energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} that measures energy output
per energy input from other portions of the economy.

\textbf{Useful energy}\index{useful energy} 
is created from final energy\index{final energy}
by devices owned by the final energy purchaser. 
For example, car owners purchase gasoline\index{gasoline} (final energy\index{final energy})
that flows into a car's engine (the device)
and creates motion along a roadway (kinetic energy\index{kinetic energy}, 
the useful energy\index{useful energy} product).
Apartment dwellers purchase
electricity\index{electricity} (final energy\index{final energy}) that flows into 
a mixer (the device)
to create kinetic energy\index{kinetic energy} (useful energy\index{useful energy})
to mix the of ingredients in a recipe.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Strong and weak sustainability for resources}\index{strong sustainability}\index{weak sustainability}
\label{sec:strong_weak_sust}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

A significant sustainability challenge\index{sustainability challenges!natural resources} 
is extracting and consuming natural resources\index{resources!natural}
at a sustainable rate.
When considering the sustainability of resource extraction\index{resource extraction} and consumption, 
we can use the views on sustainability introduced 
in Section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}:
``strong'' and ``weak.''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Strong sustainability}\index{strong sustainability}
\label{sec:resources_strong_sustainability}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Resources can be classified as ``renewable''\index{resources!renewable} or
``nonrenewable,''\index{resources!nonrenewable}
based on their regeneration rates.\index{regeneration rate!of resources}
Resources, such as the Sun\index{Sun},
that are expected to exist for millennia 
are classified as renewable.
Resources that regenerate quickly (on the order of decades), 
such as forests and other biomass\index{biomass},
are also classified as renewable.
Resources that regenerate slowly or not at all, such as fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels},
are classified as nonrenewable.

Whether or not a resource is renewable affects the sustainability of its 
extraction\index{resource extraction} and consumption,
per definitions of strong\index{strong sustainability} and weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} 
given in Section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}.
A criterion for strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} is 
extracting and consuming resources 
at rates slower than their natural regeneration rates.
Thus, any consumption of a nonrewable resource is not strongly sustainable\index{strong sustainability}.

The economy, being society's metabolism,\index{economic metabolism}
depends on natural resources
for its survival.
Indeed, we can say that the economy runs on natural resources.\index{resources!natural}
All goods and the infrastructure\index{infrastructure} for all services depend on
manufactured objects of all types:
cars and the roads on which they travel, 
homes and the utilities that sustain life,
food and the refrigerators\index{refrigerator} that maintain freshness,
toilets and the sewer systems that remove wastes\index{waste}.
Furthermore, the operation of all these systems requires energy, 
the master resource\index{master resource (energy)}.

Although any raw material can be essential 
(and not economically substitutable) 
for a given product,
the European Commission\index{European Commission} 
maintains a list of \textbf{critical raw materials (CRMs)}\index{critical raw materials (CRMs)}
with special importance 
across a wide range of industries;
see Table~\ref{tab:CRMs}.
Notice the large number of resources that are considered ``critical.''
Energy is important for running an economy but so are material resources\index{material resources}.

Another interesting feature of Table~\ref{tab:CRMs} is the breadth of applications; 
most of the critical materials are used throughout the economy.
A material may be critical to a region, to an economic sector, or to an economy as a whole 
for many reasons: 
breadth of application, 
supply vulnerability or volatility, or
supply limits.

Each region or sector will have its own list of CRMs.
For example, the transition to a renewable-energy\index{renewable energy} future 
(Section~\ref{sec:low_carbon_transition})
depends on a large number of critical materials, 
outlined in a recent International Energy Agency (IEA)\index{International Energy Agency (IEA)} report~\cite{IEA:2021wt}.
The point isn't which materials are critical for any given economy or sector;
the point is that all sectors of all economies depend upon a large number of raw materials.

