The rate at which the world's economy has been extracting resources
to create products, create infrastructure\index{infrastructure}, and deal with wastes\index{waste}
has been growing in recent decades.
% In fact, when the economy grows, the demand for goods and services grows.
% When the demand for goods and services grows, 
% the demand for natural resources grows, too.
Economic growth, by definition, means an increasing demand for goods and services,
which, in turn, means an increasing demand for natural resources.
Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} shows the growing
rate of extraction\index{resource extraction} of materials from the Earth.
Figure~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use}
shows the same data on a per-capita basis.
Although a (hypothetically) falling global population might help humanity to become 
sustainable by reducing the number of people who need resources,
Figure~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use} indicates population decline won't be
enough. 
Per-capita material consumption is climbing upward over time, 
driven in part by rising affluence~\Aparen{}.
Thus, a declining population would help humanity to be more sustainable
only if population declines faster than affluence rises.

Furthermore, Figure~\ref{fig:per_gdp_material_use} shows that on a per-GDP basis 
extraction\index{resource extraction} of construction minerals\index{construction minerals},
ores, and fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels} scales 
quite well with GDP;
those bands are not appreciably growing or shrinking over time.
On the other hand, the per-GDP extraction rate of biomass\index{biomass extraction} is declining rapidly.
The world's economies are dematerializing\index{dematerialization}, but 
only because we're using less biomass\index{biomass} per unit of GDP than ever before.
We are using nearly the same amount (mass) of construction minerals\index{construction minerals},
ores, and fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}
per GDP as we ever have.
And because GDP is growing, total material use grows, too.


