Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} 
shows that resource consumption is growing through time.
By the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion,
any extraction\index{resource extraction} of
construction minerals\index{construction minerals}, 
ores\index{ores} and industrial minerals\index{industrial minerals}, and
fossil energy carriers\index{fossil fuels}
is unsustainable, because
we are extracting these materials at rates that are faster than their regeneration rates.
The fact that we are increasing our rate of material extraction\index{resource extraction}
means that we are running well afoul of the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion
for these materials.
On the other hand,
extraction of biomass\index{biomass extraction} could be sustainable if
the extraction rate is less than the regrowth rate.
Unfortunately, Figure~\ref{fig:per_gdp_material_use} shows that biomass extraction\index{biomass extraction}
is not scaling with GDP.
In fact, GDP growth is supported exclusively by unsustainable material extraction\index{resource extraction}.

By the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion, 
we live in an unsustainable world!


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Weak sustainability}\index{weak sustainability}
\label{sec:resources_weak_sustainability}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

A weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion is that resources are extracted slowly enough
to invent and deploy substitute(s) at scale before the resource is depleted.
A similar weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion can be established for wastes\index{waste}.
Wastes\index{waste} should be emitted slowly enough for their accumulation in the environment
to pose no problems before remediation technologies can be invented and deployed
at scale to dispose of the wastes\index{waste}.
A time horizon is needed for evaluating the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion,
typically 50 years.
Thus, extraction of a resource is weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} so long as
the remaining stock is sufficient to last 50 years at today's extraction rate
(and, possibly expected future extraction rates).
Likewise, emission of wastes\index{waste} is weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} so long as 
remediation technologies will be deployed 
to ameliorate the wastes\index{waste} within 50 years.

To evaluate whether extraction of a resource meets the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion,
the following steps can be performed.
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Establish the virgin material stock as of today, 
        often called the ``reserves'' of the resource.

  \item Divide the virgin stock by 50~years to obtain 
        the average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$).

  \item Find the current rate of extraction and suitably adjust 
        for any future increases or decreases~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).

  \item Compare the weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$)
        and the current or future extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).
        If the current or future extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!) is greater than
        the average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$),
        consumption of the resource does not meet the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion.

\end{enumerate}
%
A similar approach can be used for emission of wastes\index{waste}, like CO$_2$.
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Establish the amount of waste\index{waste} in the environment, the maximum allowable
        amount of waste\index{waste} in the environment as of today, and the 
        rate at which the ecosystem\index{ecosystem} renders the waste\index{waste} inert.
  
  \item Establish the ``budget'' for waste\index{waste} emission by subtracting the 
        amount of waste\index{waste} in the environment from the maximum allowable waste\index{waste} in the environment. 
        
  \item Divide the budget by 50~years and subtract the rate at which the ecosystem\index{ecosystem} 
        renders the waste\index{waste} inert.
        The result is the maximum allowable waste\index{waste} emission rate
        for weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability}~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$).

  \item Find the current rate of waste\index{waste} emission and suitably adjust 
        for any future increases or decreases~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).

  \item Compare the weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$)
        and the current or future emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!).
        If the current or future emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!) is greater than
        the average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} emission rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$),
        emissions of the waste\index{waste} do not meet the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion.

\end{enumerate}

The parameter $\rho$ quantifies the current extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!)
as a percentage above (positive)
or below (negative)
the average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability}
extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$).

\begin{equation} \label{eq:perc_above_ws}
  \rho \equiv \frac{\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}} - \mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}}{\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}} \times \text{100}
\end{equation}
%
A positive value for $\rho$ indicates the percentage by which the extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!)
is above the average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$)
and is, therefore, weakly unsustainable. 
A negative value for $\rho$ indicates the percentage by which the extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{cf}}$\;\!)
is below the average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} extraction rate~($\mft{r}_{\mft{ws}}$)
and is, therefore, weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability}. 
A value for $\rho$ of 100\% means that the resource is being extracted at twice
its average maximum weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability} extraction rate.
Put another way, $\rho$ = 100\% means that the resource would be exhausted in 25~years, 
not 50~years.

Figure~\ref{fig:PercentageOfSustainable} shows the result of applying
the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} analysis approach
to two chemical elements (zinc\index{zinc (Zn)} and germanium\index{germanium (Ge)}) and
to worldwide emission of CO$_2$.
The world is far above
weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} levels of consumption for these two materials 
and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}.
