\section{Recycling and substitution}\index{recycling}\index{substitution}
\label{sec:recycling}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Two ways to become more sustainable are recycling\index{recycling} and substitution\index{substitution}.
Recycling\index{recycling} is a way to extend the usable life
of natural resources and
reduce rates of resource extraction\index{resource extraction}.
Recycling\index{recycling} uses discarded products as feedstock\index{feedstock}
to generate usable products.
Examples include paper recycling\index{paper recycling} to pulp 
and glass recycling\index{glass recycling} to new containers.
However, recycling\index{recycling} requires energy
and other natural resources
for transporting used material to recycling centers\index{recycling center} and 
processing used material into recycled products.
For example, paper recycling\index{paper recycling} uses water for cleaning and de-inking processes.
Glass recycling\index{glass recycling} requires high-temperature heat for melting processes.
Whether recycling\index{recycling} is, itself, a sustainable means of producing usable products
depends on the strong\index{strong sustainability} or
weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} of the recycling\index{recycling} process.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Economist Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen\index{Georgescu-Roegen, Nicholas} proposed a fourth law of thermodynamics,
stating that complete recycling\index{recycling} of matter is impossible~\cite{Georgescu-Roegen:1986aa}
because material resources\index{material resources} are subject to irreversible degradation.
(Georgescu-Roegen\index{Georgescu-Roegen, Nicholas}
was arguing by analogy from the second law of thermodynamics\index{second law of thermodynamics},
which states that all forms of energy are subject to irreversible degradation.)
Later, physicist and economist Robert Ayres correctly
argued that the second law of thermodynamics\index{second law of thermodynamics} applies only to energy
(not to materials) and that
a stable, steady-state recycling\index{recycling} system could exist
provided that two conditions are met:
(a)~a large stockpile of waste\index{waste} material exists 
    (so energy to obtain the waste\index{waste} material is small) and
(b)~an exogenous source, such as the Sun\index{Sun}, supplies energy freely and
    at sufficient rate for reprocessing of discarded material~\cite{Ayres:1999}.

The importance of energy is evident,
even in a debate about the viability of recycling\index{recycling}!
\end{mcframe}

Substitution\index{substitution} in manufacturing or production is the process of replacing
use of a valuable, scarce, or nonrenewable resource
with a less valuable, less scarce, or renewable resource.%
\footnote{
  For a related discussion of substitution\index{substitution},
  see \ref{question:consumption_substitution}.
}
Replacing use of a scarce resource with use of an abundant resource
usually extends the time horizon for depleting the scarce resource and
brings us closer to weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability}.

Scarce resources\index{resources, scarce} tend to be valuable.
Abundant resources\index{resources, abundant} tend to be less valuable.
Using an abundant resource instead of a scarce resource in a manufacturing environment 
therefore typically makes sense from a cost perspective.
However, substitution\index{substitution} is possible only when the two resources in question
are identical or nearly identical
such that they can serve the same purpose in a manufacturing or production environment.
Examples of substitution\index{substitution} include:
replacing coated steel (expensive) automobile\index{automobile} interior parts with
injection-molded plastics (inexpensive),
replacing Styrofoam hamburger containers (nonrenewable)
with paper or cardboard wrappings (renewable), and
use of solar electricity\index{solar electricity} (renewable)
instead of coal electricity\index{coal electricity} (nonrenewable).
Switching from consuming nonrenewable resources
to consuming renewable resources
is an important aspect of sustainability, for both
the weak\index{weak sustainability} and 
the strong\index{strong sustainability} versions.%
\footnote{
  In some cases, renewable resources still have sustainability impacts.
  For example, biomass\index{biomass} is a renewable-energy\index{renewable energy} source, 
  but burning wood can lead to reduced air quality.
}

That said, there are important limits to substitutability\index{substitution}.
At a manufacturing plant, the type of electricity\index{electricity}
(for example, coal electricity\index{coal electricity} or solar electricity\index{solar electricity})
is immaterial,
so long as both options are (for the U.S.) 120~V at 60~Hz.
From the point of view of the manufacturing plant,
coal electricity\index{coal electricity} and solar electricity\index{solar electricity} are 
perfect substitutes.
However, at the point of electricity generation\index{electricity generation}, 
the feedstocks\index{feedstock} for electricity\index{electricity} production are not substitutes\index{substitution}.
Coal-fired Rankine-cycle\index{Rankine cycle} power plants\index{coal-fired power plant}
cannot use the Sun's energy to make electricity\index{solar electricity}.
Similarly, a pile of coal\index{coal} is useless
to solar photovoltaic\index{solar photovoltaic electricity} farms.

Sometimes a scarce (and expensive), renewable resource is replaced by a
less-expensive, nonrenewable alternative.
Two examples illustrate.
The first involves ocean-going vessels.
In the age of sail, ships were made of timber\index{timber}, with teak\index{teak} and mahogany\index{mahogany} being
favored ship-building woods.
Today, cargo ships are made of steel, and pleasure craft are made almost exclusively
of glass-fiber reinforced polymer composites, both of which are non-renewable materials.
Teak\index{teak} and mahogany\index{mahogany}, despite being renewable,
are now too rare and too expensive for shipbuilding,
both in terms of material cost and
labor cost\index{labor cost}.
As often happens, the ready availability of less-expensive vessels
means that many more boats are purchased and used, 
bringing us further from sustainability.

The second example involves lighting\index{lighting}.
Societies moved away from wax candles\index{wax candles} and whale oil lanterns\index{lantern!whale oil} to
``town gas\index{lantern!town gas},'' kerosene\index{lantern!kerosene}, and finally, electric lights\index{electric lamp}.
Electricity\index{fossil-fuel electricity} (from fossil fuels)\index{fossil-fuel electricity} is not renewable, so 
this is another example of an 
inexpensive, nonrenewable resource substituting for an
expensive, renewable resource.

In both cases (ships and lights), none of the options
(wood ships, steel ships,
wax candles\index{wax candles}, whale oil lanterns\index{lantern!whale oil},
kerosene lanterns\index{lantern!kerosene}, or electric lights\index{electric lamp})
meets the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion.
However, all of wood ships, wax candles\index{wax candles}, whale oil lanterns\index{lantern!whale oil}, 
town gas lamps\index{lantern!town gas}, and
kerosene lamps\index{lantern!kerosene} proved to be weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability}.
We found substitutes for the expensive natural resources
in a reasonable time frame and
before they were depleted;
see \ref{question:weak_sust_good_enough}
for discussion of whether weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} is ``good enough.''


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Example: energy}
\label{sec:energy_as_prime_example}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

It has been argued
(as in Section~\ref{sec:masterE})
that energy is
the master resource~\cite{library1971energy}\index{master resource (energy)}
for two important reasons.
First, energy is required
for extraction\index{resource extraction} of all natural resources (including energy itself),
for any material transformation,
for consuming goods and services, and
for disposing of goods.
Second, energy is fungible.
Within the limits of the second law of thermodynamics\index{second law of thermodynamics},
energy in one form can be converted to energy in any other form
using suitable machines.
An automobile\index{automobile} converts chemical potential energy (gasoline\index{gasoline})
to kinetic energy\index{kinetic energy} (car motion).
A hairdryer\index{hairdryer} converts electricity\index{grid electricity} (from the grid)
to heat (applied to hair).
A solar panel\index{solar panel} converts solar energy (from the Sun\index{Sun})
to electricity\index{electricity} (for use in many devices, including, possibly, hair dryers\index{hairdryer}).

Because energy is the master resource,\index{master resource (energy)}
we use energy as the prime example in the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity} (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}).
There are two important questions:
where are we using energy and
are we using energy sustainably?
Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey}
is an energy \textbf{Sankey diagram}\index{Sankey diagram!energy}%
\footnote{
  Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} is a Sankey diagram\index{Sankey diagram},
  a diagram in which the width of the lines is proportional to the magnitude of the flows.
}
that answers the first question
for the U.S.
Energy is used in four broad sectors of the economy:
residences, commerce, industry, and transportation.
Industry and transportation use more energy than residences and commerce.

