  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

 
Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus} shows that
the primary energy intensity\index{primary energy intensity} of the world economy~\REpparen{} has fallen from
15 to 4~MJ/2017 international dollar across the last two centuries.
The decline is caused by the fact that the world economy's GDP
(Figure~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus})
has been growing at a faster rate (in \%/yr terms) than primary energy consumption\index{primary energy consumption}
(Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}).
The decline indicates that each additional dollar of GDP
is created with incrementally less primary energy consumption\index{primary energy consumption}.

While the decrease in \REp{}
(the prime example for \mft{R} in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX})
appears to be good news for sustainability
(declining \mft{R} puts downward pressure on \mft{I} in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}), 
Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus} shows that 
the most important cause of decreasing primary energy consumption\index{primary energy consumption} per unit GDP
is declining consumption of biomass\index{biomass}.
Ironically, the decreases in \REp{} are coming from reduction in per-GDP consumption 
of a type of energy that is possibly sustainable, biomass\index{biomass}!

We can use these data to learn things about the IPARX\index{IPARX identity} terms
(Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}) and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}.
A narrowed version of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX},
considers only CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}
on the left-hand side of the equation~($\mft{I}_{\text{CO}_2}$)
and the energy intensity of economic activity~\REpparen{}
instead of \mft{R} on the right-hand side.
When \REp{} falls, downward pressure is placed on CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}.
Whether CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions} actually decrease
depends on the rates of increase or decline of the other terms
on the right side of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}.
Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph} shows that CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!growth}
have been growing over time.
So, other terms on the right side of the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity}
must be growing collectively faster than energy intensity of the economy is declining;
see Section~\ref{sec:revisit_IPARX}.


