\section{Patterns of resource extraction and resource transitions}\index{resource extraction}
\label{sec:resource_transitions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Extraction of finite resources\index{resource extraction}
(such as coal\index{coal}, oil\index{crude oil}, natural gas\index{natural gas},
lithium\index{lithium (Li)}, neodymium\index{neodymium (Nd)}, phosphorous\index{phosphorous (P)}, or helium\index{helium (He)})
follows a pattern through time~\cite{Brandt:2007vt}.
In the beginning, extraction of a useful but finite resource\index{resource extraction} accelerates
as demand climbs and technologies are developed to reduce the cost of extraction.
Through time, the resource extraction\index{resource extraction} rate peaks then and declines.
A clear example of a production curve for a finite resource is
extraction of coal\index{coal} in the UK\index{United Kingdom (UK)}, shown in Figure~\ref{fig:UK_coal_extraction}.

<<UK_coal_extraction, fig.scap="UK coal production vs.\\ time", fig.cap="UK\\index{United Kingdom (UK)} coal\\index{coal} production vs.\\ time. \\emph{Sources}: \\citet{Rutledge:2011, Rutledge:tv}\\index{Rutledge, David} for 1830--2009; \\citet{UK_dept_BEIS:2021} for 2010--2020.">>=
