                                         sheet = "data to plot") %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    Year = as.numeric(Year)
  ) %>%
  dplyr::filter(
    complete.cases(.)
  )

uk_coal_extraction %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year, y = UK_coal_production_Mt)) +
  ggplot2::geom_line(size = 1, colour = mc_title_blue) +

  ggplot2::labs(x = ggplot2::element_blank(),
                y = "UK coal production [Mt/yr]") +

  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

The cumulative production of a limited resource follows a logistic curve,
with an inflection point (from concave upward to concave downward)
at the production peak
and leveling toward the end;
see Figure~\ref{fig:UK_coal_logistic}.

<<UK_coal_logistic, fig.scap="UK coal production logistic curve vs.\\ time", fig.cap="UK coal production logistic curve vs.\\ time. \\emph{Sources}: \\citet{Rutledge:2011, Rutledge:tv}\\index{Rutledge, David} for 1829--2009; own calculations for 2010--2020.">>=
uk_coal_extraction %>%
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes(x = Year, y = q_Gt)) +
  ggplot2::geom_line(size = 1, colour = mc_title_blue) +

  ggplot2::labs(x = ggplot2::element_blank(),
                y = "UK coal cumulative production [Gt]") +

  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@

In the case of the UK\index{United Kingdom (UK)}, substitution\index{substitution} away from coal\index{coal} 
for electricity generation\index{electricity generation} 
is occurring. 
Coal\index{coal} production is now dominated 
by China\index{China}, India\index{India}, the U.S., and Australia\index{Australia},
but international trade is possible.
So the world will not face coal\index{coal} shortages
until all regions are exhausted of the resource.
Each region is at different places on its logistic curve
for resource production.
Other ways to substitute away from domestic coal\index{coal} for electricity\index{electricity} 
(besides switching suppliers)
include deploying natural gas\index{natural-gas electricity}, wind\index{wind electricity}, and
solar electricity\index{solar electricity} generation, 
as the UK\index{United Kingdom (UK)} is doing now.

Another way to slow down the inevitable march of time
along logistic curves for finite resources is to transition
economies to use fewer resources per unit of GDP produced,
that is, to reduce the resource intensity of economic activity~\Rparen{}.
Reduction of resource intensity of economic activity is sometimes called dematerialization\index{dematerialization}.
Reducing \mft{R} will reduce resource consumption but only if
GDP stays constant or grows more slowly than the
rate at which \mft{R} decreases.

For the prime example of energy and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions},
reducing \mft{R} means reducing the energy intensity of economic activity~\REpparen{},
that is, reducing the amount of energy required to produce
each unit of GDP.
(Section~\ref{sec:low_carbon_transition} discusses a distinct but related issue,
transitioning the energy system to reduce CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}
from each unit of energy consumed.)
There are many ways often suggested to reduce the energy intensity of economic activity~\REpparen{}.
First, increasing energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} (through efficiency standards or mandates)
can decrease the energy consumption for end uses.
Examples include \textbf{corporate average fuel economy (CAFE)}\index{corporate average fuel economy (CAFE)}
standards for vehicles in the U.S.\
and mandates for \textbf{LED lighting}\index{LED lamp} in many countries.
Another way to reduce the energy intensity of an economy is to move
away from a manufacturing economy toward a service economy.
However, as shown in the haircut\index{haircut} example at the beginning of this chapter,
the need for resources never goes away, even in a service economy.
In fact, moving to a service economy often introduces problem shifting\index{problem shifting}
(Section~\ref{sec:electric_vehicles}),
as finished goods are imported and manufacturing moves offshore~\cite{Hardt:2018aa}.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Summary}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This chapter investigated the resource intensity of economic activity~\Rparen{}.
It is clear that economies use a wide variety of resources
across all sectors of the economy.
Many resources are used unsustainably, 
as measured by both strong\index{strong sustainability} and weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criteria.
For the prime example of primary energy intensity\index{primary energy intensity} of economic activity,
we found that~\REp{} has decreased substantially since 1800, 
but only because we are using far less biofuels\index{biofuel} per dollar of GDP
today than in the past.
Fossil-fuel\index{fossil fuels} use has remained much more constant on a per-GDP basis.
Ironically, biofuels\index{biofuel} are a (potentially) sustainable source of energy, 
so we are growing economies with unsustainable fossil-fuel consumption\index{fossil fuels!combustion} 
while at the same time
relying less on consumption of (potentially) sustainable biomass\index{biomass}.

The next chapter looks at the impact 
of resource extraction~\Xparen{}, 
the final term in the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity}~(Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}).

 
