\begin{questions}

  \item Some aquifers, such as the Ogallala aquifer\index{Ogallala aquifer},
        are called ``fossil water''\index{fossil water}
        because they were filled with glacial melt from the last ice age.
        Is using any such resource sustainable?
        What are the moral and ethical implications of leaving a valuable and
        usable resource unused? \label{question:ogallala}

  \item What is the purpose (telos\index{telos}) of mineral resources\index{mineral resources} in the environment?
        Should they be left in place or used?
        Humans are the only creatures on Earth that make use of most minerals\index{minerals}.
        What are some positive impacts on animal populations that arise from
        humans' use of materials that are not available to any other animal?
        Are there any?

  \item What are the positive features of the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion?
        What are the weaknesses of the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion?
        Is the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion too severe for modern life today?
        Justify your answer.
        Can strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} be applied selectively to some resources but
        not others or should all resources be judged equally?
        What are the implications of not applying the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability}
        criterion universally to all resources?

  \item Why is the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion a good criterion?
        What are the drawbacks to weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criteria?
        What is the basis for your judgment?

  \item In which circumstances is a weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion appropriate?
        In which circumstances is the strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} criterion appropriate?
        Is weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} good enough?
        Give examples.\label{question:weak_sust_good_enough}

  \item Time is our most constrained resource. The human lifespan is about 4000 weeks.
        How do you use your time?
        What fraction of your total time is devoted to
        economically productive activities? Why?
        What are the sustainability impacts of how you spend your time?
        Can you quantify the sustainability impacts of how you spend your time
        in terms of the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity}?

  \item Where does your water come from?
        How does it get to you? Where is your waste water\index{waste water} treated?
        How is energy, the master resource\index{master resource (energy)}, involved in each of these steps?
        How has water provision changed over time where you live?

  \item Evaluate the notion of a closed-loop water system (so called ``toilet-to-tap''\index{toilet-to-tap}).
        Would you drink water from a toilet-to-tap\index{toilet-to-tap} system?
        Does your answer change if you learn that, already, there are low levels
        of many pharmaceutical substances and organic pollutants in drinking water?
        A closed-loop water system would probably lower exposure to some pollutants
        and increase concentrations of pharmaceutical substances (or else require
        more advanced waste-water\index{waste water} treatment technology).
        How does a closed-loop system affect sustainability for communities that
        use it? Other communities?

  \item Carbon-driven global climate change\index{climate change} and population growth\index{population growth} are making
        desalination of seawater a more prominent source of water for
        many populations.
        Carbon emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!desalination} from desalination may increase from 76 million
        tonnes of CO$_2$ per year in 2015 to 200--500 million tonnes per year by 2040
        \cite{GCWDA2015}.
        % see also Rothausen, S., Conway, D. Greenhouse-gas emissions from energy use in the water sector.
        % Nature Clim Change 1, 210219 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1038/nclimate1147
        \begin{enumerate}
        \item Is there an individual right to water?
        \item Do nation states have a right to water?
        \item Does it matter if you're oil-rich Saudi Arabia\index{Saudi Arabia} or the (relatively) poor
              and low-lying Republic of the Marshall Islands\index{Republic of the Marshall Islands (RMI)}?
        \item Discuss how these rights impact global efforts to limit climate change\index{climate change}.
        \end{enumerate}

  \item Consider a carbon tax\index{carbon tax} on commercial transportation.
        Is such a tax\index{carbon tax} a reduction in affluence (Chapter~\ref{chap:affluence})
        because the same goods you previously purchased now cost more?
        Or would you view the tax\index{carbon tax} as a enriching your natural capital\index{natural capital} by
        incentivizing a shift to carbon-free forms of energy (thereby providing
        you with all the benefits of a stronger ecosystem\index{ecosystem}; see \ref{question:shell_lawsuit})?
        What beliefs or values inform your answer?
        How might such an evaluation be extended from the personal to a national
        or global scale?

  \item The weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion
        in Section~\ref{sec:resources_weak_sustainability} is predicated on
        renewable substitutes being found for nonrenewable resources.
